<subSubSection id="C3266529FFBCFFA9FF5CF9A6DCD8F9A4" box="[151,1177,1543,1570]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="8B8336A2FFBCFFA9FF5CF9A6DCD8F9A4" blockId="2.[151,1437,1543,2038]" box="[151,1177,1543,1570]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">
<emphasis id="B948EAB0FFBCFFA9FF5CF9A6D904F9A4" bold="true" box="[151,325,1543,1570]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">Type material.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation id="3B543CFFFFBCFFA9FE87F9A9DA8AF9A4" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3750353330" box="[332,715,1543,1570]" collectorName="Conradt." country="Cameroon" location="Kamerun" pageId="2" pageNumber="327" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
<typeStatus id="54878800FFBCFFA9FE87F9A9D9F8F9A4" box="[332,441,1543,1569]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">Holotype</typeStatus>
: 
<collectingCountry id="F32B7632FFBCFFA9FE08F9A6DA6FF9A7" box="[451,558,1544,1570]" name="Cameroon" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">Kamerun</collectingCountry>
, leg. 
<collectorName id="26C95374FFBCFFA9FDA2F9A9DA8AF9A4" box="[617,715,1543,1569]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">Conradt.</collectorName>
</materialsCitation>
<typeStatus id="54878800FFBCFFA9FD1AF9A9DB78F9A4" box="[721,825,1543,1569]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">Holotype</typeStatus>
lost (Hamburg), not examined.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3266529FFBCFFA9FF0CF985D9CFF97C" pageId="2" pageNumber="327" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B8336A2FFBCFFA9FF0CF985D9CFF97C" blockId="2.[151,1437,1543,2038]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">
<emphasis id="B948EAB0FFBCFFA9FF0CF985D97BF9C0" bold="true" box="[199,314,1579,1605]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">Diagnosis</emphasis>
(transcribed, inferred). Body length 
<quantity id="4CC49B47FFBCFFA9FD2AF985DB7DF9C3" box="[737,828,1579,1606]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="327" unit="mm" value="3.5">3.5 mm</quantity>
, colour light shiny brown, vestiture of mixed shorter and longer setae. Antennal scapus as long as funiculus and club combined, with scant setae; club without sutures. Pronotum narrowly rounded in front, subconical, sides carinate, anteriorly rugose with rough asperities, on posterior part with sparse, deep punctures. Elytra with striae distinctly punctured, declivity steep, with several distinct round spines, posterior margin elevated, suture inside heavily punctured. Protibiae broad, lateral edge evenly curved, with three lateral denticles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3266529FFBCFFA9FF0CF8ADD9A5F89B" box="[199,484,1795,1822]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B8336A2FFBCFFA9FF0CF8ADD9A5F89B" blockId="2.[151,1437,1543,2038]" box="[199,484,1795,1822]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">
<emphasis id="B948EAB0FFBCFFA9FF0CF8ADD920F898" bold="true" box="[199,353,1795,1821]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="F32B7632FFBCFFA9FEACF8AAD99EF89B" box="[359,479,1796,1822]" name="Cameroon" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3266529FFBCFFA8FF0CF886DA3AFEE0" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="328" pageId="2" pageNumber="327" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8336A2FFBCFFA9FF0CF886DCE6F80C" blockId="2.[151,1437,1543,2038]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">
<emphasis id="B948EAB0FFBCFFA9FF0CF886D97AF8C7" bold="true" box="[199,315,1832,1858]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">Remarks.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus id="54878800FFBCFFA9FEB3F886D9E9F8C7" box="[376,424,1832,1858]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">type</typeStatus>
was lost during the World War II bombing of Hamburg and no other material is known (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B53FFBCFFA9FF55F8E5D9E5F8E3" author="Wood, S. L. &amp; Bright, D. E." box="[158,420,1867,1894]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327" pagination="1 - 1553" refId="ref10748" refString="Wood, S. L. &amp; Bright, D. E. (1992) A catalog of Scolytidae and Platypodidae (Coleoptera). Part 2: Taxonomic index. Great Basin Naturalist Memoirs, 13, 1 - 1553." type="journal article" year="1992">Wood and Bright 1992</bibRefCitation>
). It will therefore likely remain as a ghost species for all future studies. However, the illustration of the antenna and protibia (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B53FFBCFFA9FDE9F8C1DA98F80F" author="Hagedorn, J. M." box="[546,729,1903,1930]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327" pagination="733 - 746" refId="ref9953" refString="Hagedorn, J. M. (1909) Diagnosen bischer unbeschriebener Borkenkafer (Col.). Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift, 1909, 733 - 746." type="journal article" year="1909">Hagedorn, 1909</bibRefCitation>
) refute any association with Micracidini.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8336A2FFBCFFA8FF0CF83DDA3AFEE0" blockId="2.[151,1437,1543,2038]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,358]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="328" pageId="2" pageNumber="327">
The description is very poor on details. Except for the rather large size, it is notable for its rounded spines on the declivity and it has an elevated rim along the posterior margin of the elytra. The antennal scapus is elongated and the club is without sutures (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B53FFBCFFA9FE6CF875DA23F873" author="Hagedorn, J. M." box="[423,610,2011,2038]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327" pagination="733 - 746" refId="ref9953" refString="Hagedorn, J. M. (1909) Diagnosen bischer unbeschriebener Borkenkafer (Col.). Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift, 1909, 733 - 746." type="journal article" year="1909">Hagedorn, 1909</bibRefCitation>
: figure 42; reprinted in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B53FFBCFFA9FCA4F875DC47F873" author="Schedl, K. E." box="[879,1030,2011,2038]" pageId="2" pageNumber="327" pagination="1 - 594" refId="ref10525" refString="Schedl, K. E. (1962) Scolytidae und Platypodidae Afrikas. Band II. Familie Scolytidae (Fortsetzung). Unterfamilie Ipinae (Fortsetzung). Revista de Entomologia de Mocambique, 5, 1 - 594." type="journal article" year="1962">Schedl, 1962</bibRefCitation>
). The protibiae are laterally broadly rounded, with three presumably socketed denticles along its margin (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAD4B53FFBDFFA8FC6EFF39DC1BFF34" author="Hagedorn, J. M." box="[933,1114,151,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="328" pagination="733 - 746" refId="ref9953" refString="Hagedorn, J. M. (1909) Diagnosen bischer unbeschriebener Borkenkafer (Col.). Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift, 1909, 733 - 746." type="journal article" year="1909">Hagedorn 1909</bibRefCitation>
: figure 43). These three features are similar in shape to some species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D21FFBDFFA8FD59FF15DB58FF51" authorityName="K.E.Schedl" authorityYear="1957" box="[658,793,187,212]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Mimiocurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B948EAB0FFBDFFA8FD59FF15DB58FF51" box="[658,793,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="328">Mimiocurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, especially the 
<typeStatus id="54878800FFBDFFA8FC01FF15DBBBFF50" box="[970,1018,187,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="328">type</typeStatus>
species 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D21FFBDFFA8FB91FF15DDDDFF50" authority="Schedl, 1957" authorityName="Schedl" authorityYear="1957" box="[1114,1436,186,213]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Mimiocurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acuminatus">
<emphasis id="B948EAB0FFBDFFA8FB91FF15DD40FF51" box="[1114,1281,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="328">M. acuminatus</emphasis>
Schedl, 1957
</taxonomicName>
and related species. It is also possible that 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D21FFBDFFA8FDA6FF71DB4CFF7D" baseAuthorityName="Hagedorn" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[621,781,223,248]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Pseudomicracis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="camerunus">
<emphasis id="B948EAB0FFBDFFA8FDA6FF71DB4CFF7D" box="[621,781,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="328">M. camerunus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is related to a species group in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D21FFBDFFA8FBA2FF71D88EFE98" authority="Blandford, 1894" authorityName="Blandford" authorityYear="1894" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Acanthotomicus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B948EAB0FFBDFFA8FBA2FF71DD5CFF7C" box="[1129,1309,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="328">Acanthotomicus</emphasis>
Blandford, 1894
</taxonomicName>
where the antennal club bear few traces of sutures and where some species have only a few rounded spines on the declivity. However, Hagedorn was sufficiently familiar with 
<taxonomicName id="4C3C4D21FFBDFFA8FC43FE89DC37FEC4" authority="Eggers, 1932" authorityName="Eggers" authorityYear="1932" box="[904,1142,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Mimips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B948EAB0FFBDFFA8FC43FE89DB9DFEC5" box="[904,988,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="328">Mimips</emphasis>
Eggers, 1932
</taxonomicName>
(the more frequently used named at that time) to know the difference.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
